The simplest fix: keep backward compatibility. Since tests create instances with a single arg, I need to make the old constructor still work. The best approach is to remove `@Value` from `updateOnlyRoot` by initializing it directly with a default value. But `@Value` makes all fields constructor parameters.

Let me use a different approach: I can define the `updateOnlyRoot` field with a default value and exclude it from the generated constructor. In Lombok, you can't do this directly with `@Value`. Let me restructure the class slightly.

The simplest approach: don't use `@Value` for `updateOnlyRoot` - instead, just initialize it directly with a default value `false` (or `null`). But in `@Value`, all fields become `final` and are set via the constructor.

Wait - actually, let me look at this more carefully. The `@Value` annotation is on the class `UpdateScmFromGitOrigin`. If I add a new field, it becomes part of the all-args constructor. The test code calls `new UpdateScmFromGitOrigin(null)` - this was okay when there was only one `@Nullable` field.

The solution is to write a custom constructor that handles this. Since `@Value` with a custom constructor won't generate another one, I'll write my own:

